	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				In my opinion, it's a waste of a spell-- since there are so many ways to get an idea of where you are (for free, and without the use of mana!). I really wish they'd replace this with something good. Perhaps like a spell maybe like &quot;Pathfinder&quot; Or &quot;Landmarkfinder&quot; where when you cast the spell if you're lost, it'll gate you to the nearest town/path/safe spot, in order for you to get to where you want to be. Kind of like gate, but not to the binding point. It would be kind of cool to have something like that. For those who can't be bothered and really want a true north, they can always sell a 'compass' item for everyone...<BR>
<BR>
As for finding your way without the aid of the spell, firstly, in EQ, the sun seems to rise in the North, and set in the South. If it's daytime, you can generally tell where north is with the sun. Doesn't work at night, but like the previos post says,  you can drop a sword. (Even though I haven't tried that).<BR>
<BR>
Secondly, /loc has saved me many more times than True North ever will. Doing /loc will give you an X/Y location, in numbers. The first number tells you how far North/South you are. The higher the number, the further North you are, the lower, the further south you are. So if you do a /loc in a position, then step forward and do another /loc, AND the first number has gone up, you have a rough idea that you're facing north. If it goes down, you're heading south. Allakhazam explains the /loc function better than I-- it's something you really need to learn, otherwise you step in Neriak or Toxx or Kethelin floor and you're lost. So check out his site: http//:eq.stomped.com  and, read up on the /location function in his 'index' page. Also, if you know something is somewhere and just /ooc a &quot;Whats the loc to so and so?&quot; Usually someone will know.<BR>
<BR>
Thirdly, Sure sense heading has a high failure rate, but if you're chilling waiting for your mana/health to go up, hotkey sense heading and just press the key over and over and over, and eventually, you'll be able to sense head without waiting to long for it to succeed.<BR>
<BR>
Fourthly, Another good way for people go get back to towns is to use guards, by tracking. This is really limited to druids, and rangers, however, If you get the tracking skill, is something to do, if you get lost. Also good for parties who have these in theirs. If you say want to find the Erudin gate from Tox, and are lost, you can wander around aimlessly until you track a NPC which you know is near the gate. Kinda like using a NPC as a landmark. I've gotten lost a few times in Toxxulia so I wander (or I /loc) until I see &quot;Sentinel Flavius&quot; on my track screen, and so I track him and get home with comfort. Not so good for everyone, but an option nonetheless.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
